Luigi uses the multiprocessing module to manage worker tasks, and uses `multiprocessing.Process.terminate()` to implement worker timeout. However, as [mentioned in the docs](https://docs.python.org/2/library/multiprocessing.html#multiprocessing.Process.terminate), terminate orphans subprocesses spawned by the task. Maybe there are good reasons for orphaning these processes instead of killing them. However, it was leading to large resource leaks in my application -- I'm assuming most luigi workflows want subprocesses to be cleaned up during a worker timeout.

The psutil module seems to make recursively terminating a process and its subprocesses straightforward (though I've only tested this on one machine). I'm not sure if you'd be keen on adding `psutil` as a required dependency, so I've proposed a solution that falls back to the default terminate behavior if it isn't available.

Here's a script to demonstrate the issue

```python
from subprocess import check_call
import luigi


class Worker(luigi.Task):

    foo = luigi.Parameter()

    def output(self):
        return luigi.LocalTarget(self.foo)

    def run(self):
        check_call(['python', '-c', 'import time; time.sleep(1000)'])


class Test(luigi.Task):

    def requires(self):
        return [Worker(foo="_%i" % i) for i in range(5)]

    def output(self):
        return luigi.LocalTarget('done')


if __name__ == "__main__":
    luigi.run()
```
Invoked via
```
python test.py Test --worker-timeout=3 --workers 5 --local-scheduler
```

With this patch, `ps` shows 5 processes of `python -c import time; time.sleep(1000)` while the pipeline is running, and 0 when completed. Without the patch, those 5 processes stay alive + orphaned.

When I was merging a node’s multiple meshes into that node’s first mesh’s primitives, I was deleting the merged meshes from the node.

However, I wasn’t deleting the merged meshes from the mAsset->meshes Dict, causing the gltf2 export to contain extra unreferenced meshes and duplicate primitives.

This would cause an output like this:

```json
"meshes": [
    {
         "primitives": [
             {
                 "mode": 4,
                 "material": 1,
                 "indices": 4,
                 "attributes": {
                     "POSITION": 1,
                     "NORMAL": 2,
                     "TEXCOORD_0": 3
                 }
             },
             {
                 "mode": 4,
                 "material": 1,
                 "indices": 8,
                 "attributes": {
                     "POSITION": 5,
                     "NORMAL": 6,
                     "TEXCOORD_0": 7
                 }
             }
        ]
    },
    {
        "primitives": [
            {
                 "mode": 4,
                 "material": 1,
                 "indices": 8,
                 "attributes": {
                     "POSITION": 5,
                     "NORMAL": 6,
                     "TEXCOORD_0": 7
                 }
             }
        ]
    }
]
```

where the second mesh's primitive is repeated twice. The fix prevents the second mesh from being output.

---

This new code adds a new method to LazyDict, `Remove`, which removes the object from it, and updates indexes of subsequent meshes in the mObjs vector property. However, the method does not take care of updating the indexes in `Ref`s of `Mesh`es, so that has to be done separately.

This is proposed instead of #56 , to reduce the typing required (`asynchronous` vs `wait`).

Note: Upstream dependency `pyhive` has yet to be updated to avoid `async` keyword, and to maintain functionality, we do not avoid its usage there; and so this code still will not run for HiveServer2 clients, and will report syntax errors in Python 3.7 .

@danfrankj

In the case of using the following configuration, exabgp would send 2 routes with incorrect AS_PATH attributes.
```
neighbor 192.168.0.100 {
        router-id 192.168.0.1;
        local-address 192.168.0.1;
        local-as 65001;
        peer-as 65100;
        hold-time 90;

        family {
                ipv4 unicast;
        }

        static {
                route 172.16.1.0/24 {
                        origin igp;
                        as-path [ ( 65002 ) ];
                        next-hop 192.168.0.1;
                }
                route 172.16.2.0/24 {
                        origin igp;
                        as-path [ ( 65002 65003 ) ];
                        next-hop 192.168.0.1;
                }
        }
}
```
The first route would be advertised with correct AS_PATH attribute to the neighbor, but the second one would be advertised with incorrect attributes.
```
Remote router> 
   Network          Next Hop            Metric LocPrf Weight Path
*> 172.16.1.0/24    192.168.0.1                            0 {65002} i
*> 172.16.2.0/24    192.168.0.1                            0 {65002} i
```
It should be:
```
Remote router> 
   Network          Next Hop            Metric LocPrf Weight Path
*> 172.16.1.0/24    192.168.0.1                            0 {65002} i
*> 172.16.2.0/24    192.168.0.1                            0 {65002,65003} i
```
In the latest code, It seems to return [ ] even if AS_SET exists when AS_PATH doesn't have AS_SEQ.

I seemed to have made a mess with when trying to rebase the commits....

I was trying to bring this branch of the fork back to a point without all the committed changes (by reverting) and then adding the function we created for downloading and uncompresssing tar.gz files, which is needed for the Google Speech Command dataset. 

@fakufaku let me know if we should squash these commits together (and if so how). What I was doing was squashing commits that were not part of`upstream` but then I would be asked to pull from `origin` which would then create more commits! Sorry for the troubles and thanks for your help.

